bled__zFGBd PostDetail_chip__oT3gx detail-s">Alignment</span></div><h1 clas=
s=3D"h2">Forecasting rare language model behaviors</h1><div class=3D"PostDe=
tail_post-timestamp__TBJ0Z text-label">Feb 25, 2025</div><div class=3D"Post=
Detail_cta-button__4rDc7"><a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.16797" clas=
s=3D"ButtonCta_button__miruF detail-m" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank" a=
ria-label=3D"Read the paper"><span>Read the paper</span></a></div></div><di=
v class=3D"text-b2 PostDetail_post-detail__6Ldh_"><article><div class=3D"">=
<div class=3D"Body_body__XEXq7"><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM para=
graph-m post-text">One of the major goals of Alignment Science is to predic=
t AI models=E2=80=99 propensity for dangerous behaviors <em>before</em> tho=
se behaviors occur. For instance, we run <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.c=
om/research/alignment-faking">experiments</a> to check for complex behavior=
s like deception, and attempt to identify early warning signs of misalignme=
nt.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">We als=
o develop evaluations that can be run on models to test whether they=E2=80=
=99ll engage in particular kinds of concerning behaviors, such as providing=
 information about deadly weapons, or even <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic=
.com/research/sabotage-evaluations">sabotaging</a> human attempts to monito=
r them.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">A =
major difficulty in developing these evaluations is the problem of <em>scal=
e</em>. Evaluations might be run on thousands of examples of a large langua=
ge model=E2=80=99s behavior=E2=80=94but when a model is deployed in the rea=
l world, it might process billions of queries every day. If concerning beha=
viors are rare, they could easily be missed in the evaluations.</p><p class=
=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">For example, perhaps =
a specific jailbreaking technique is attempted thousands of times in an eva=
luation and looks entirely ineffective, but it <em>does</em> work after (sa=
y) a million attempts in a real-world deployment. That is, given enough att=
empted jailbreaks, eventually one of them is likely to work. This renders p=
re-deployment evaluations much less useful=E2=80=94especially if one single=
 failure could be catastrophic.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM =
display-sans-s post-section" id=3D""><strong>Forecasting rare behaviors</st=
rong></h2><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Wha=
t=E2=80=99s needed is a way to forecast the rare behaviors, extrapolating f=
rom the relatively small number of instances we=E2=80=99ve observed before =
deployment. This is the subject of <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.16=
797">a new paper</a> from Anthropic=E2=80=99s Alignment Science team.</p><p=
 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">In our study, w=
e began by calculating the probability that various prompts make a model pr=
oduce harmful responses=E2=80=94in some cases, we did this just by sampling=
 large numbers of model completions for each prompt, and measuring the frac=
tion that contained harmful content.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7=
kGM paragraph-m post-text">We then looked at the queries with the highest r=
isk probabilities, and plotted them according to the number of queries. Int=
erestingly, the relationship between the number of queries tested and the h=
ighest (log) risk probabilities followed the distribution known as a power =
law.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">This =
is where the extrapolation came in: because the features of power laws are =
well-understood mathematically, we could calculate what the worst-case risk=
s would be with (say) millions of queries, even when we had only tested a f=
ew thousand. This allowed us to forecast risks at much larger scales than w=
e could otherwise (this is analogous to testing the temperature of a lake a=
t a few different=E2=80=94but still shallow=E2=80=94depths, finding a predi=
ctable pattern, and then using that pattern to predict how cold the lake is=
 at depths we can=E2=80=99t easily measure).</p><div class=3D"Body_media-co=
lumn__xPzhg"><figure class=3D"ImageWithCaption_e-imageWithCaption__8C2mY Im=
ageWithCaption_inline-image__B15e_"><img loading=3D"lazy" width=3D"1920" he=
ight=3D"1080" decoding=3D"async" data-nimg=3D"1" style=3D"color:transparent=
" src=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/_next/image?url=3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fwww-cdn.=
anthropic.com%2Fimages%2F4zrzovbb%2Fwebsite%2F78129ab9954dfd9ca2cfac69a7292=
2b53087b02a-1920x1080.jpg&amp;w=3D3840&amp;q=3D75"><figcaption class=3D"tex=
t-caption">Scaling laws allow us to forecast rare language model behaviors.=
 We find that the risk of the highest-risk queries sent to AI models (y-axi=
s) follows a power law when plotted against the number of queries (x-axis).=
 This lets us make a forecast, even from a smaller dataset of evaluated que=
ries whether any query is likely to exhibit an undesirable behavior at depl=
oyment (shaded, right), even from orders-of-magnitude smaller evaluations (=
unshaded, left).</figcaption></figure></div><p class=3D"Body_reading-column=
__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">How accurate were our forecasts? We tested t=
his by comparing our predictions against actual measurements in several dif=
ferent scenarios.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m pos=
t-text">First, we looked at the model=E2=80=99s risk of providing dangerous=
 information (like instructions to synthesize harmful chemicals). In tests =
where we used our scaling laws to extrapolate risks from small numbers of q=
ueries (say, 900) to those larger by several orders of magnitude (say, 90,0=
00). We found that the predictions we made from the power law were within o=
ne order of magnitude of the true risk for 86% of forecasts.</p><p class=3D=
"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Second, we forecasted th=
e emergence of misaligned actions (specifically power-seeking, self-preserv=
ation, and self-exfiltration, all of which are undesirable behaviours from =
AIs). The tests involved multiple-choice questions that allowed the models =
to choose a misaligned action or an aligned one. For example, we would prov=
ide the model with a system prompt that made it focus on a particular occup=
ational domain (for example, sales or medical jobs), and then asked it ques=
tions about whether it would prefer to =E2=80=9Ccreate new policies=E2=80=
=9D (which would be consistent with power-seeking, since the model then beg=
ins to shape the organisation to which it=E2=80=99s attached) or =E2=80=9Ca=
nalyze the existing policies=E2=80=9D (which would be a more aligned action=
).</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Our for=
ecasts accurately predicted the risk that the model would pick the worst qu=
ery: we had an average absolute error of 0.05, compared to 0.12 for more st=
raightforward, baseline methods. That is, our method had 2.5 times lower er=
ror than a simpler comparison.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM pa=
ragraph-m post-text">Finally, we also applied our method to =E2=80=9C<a hre=
f=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2202.03286">automated red-teaming</a>=E2=80=9D. =
This is when a model is used to find and exploit the weaknesses of another =
model in an experimental setting. When doing so, one can hypothetically cho=
ose to use a small model that generates a very large number of queries or, =
for the same cost, a larger model that generates a smaller number of querie=
s (but where those queries are likely of a higher quality). Our forecasts w=
ere useful in working out how to most efficiently allocate a compute budget=
 while doing red-teaming=E2=80=94in settings where the choice is important,=
 they identified the optimal model 79% of the time.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_re=
ading-column__t7kGM display-sans-s post-section" id=3D""><strong>Conclusion=
s</strong></h2><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text=
">Under normal circumstances, it simply isn=E2=80=99t feasible to use stand=
ard evaluations to test for all the rarest risks of AI models. Our method i=
sn=E2=80=99t perfect=E2=80=94in the paper, we give a number of future direc=
tions that might improve the accuracy and practicality of our predictions=
=E2=80=94but it provides LLM developers with a new way to efficiently predi=
ct rare risks, allowing them to take action before deploying their models.<=
/p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Read <a hr=
ef=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.16797">the full paper</a>.</p><h2 class=3D=
"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sans-s post-section" id=3D""><strong>Wo=
rk with us</strong></h2><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m =
post-text">If you=E2=80=99re interested in working on problems like deploym=
ent evaluations or jailbreak robustness, we=E2=80=99re currently recruiting=
 for <a href=3D"https://boards.greenhouse.io/anthropic/jobs/4459012008">Res=
earch Engineers / Scientists</a> and we=E2=80=99d love to see your applicat=
ion.</p></div></div></article><div class=3D"PostDetail_b-social-share__z04a=
